WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:02.280
I think I'm going to talk here.

00:00:02.340 --> 00:00:07.560
Yeah, I hope you guys don't mind the Twitter aspect

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:07.720
.

00:00:07.730 --> 00:00:13.560
This is all obviously very translatable to Blue Sky.

00:00:13.570 --> 00:00:16.970
Yeah, my talk's about, as you can see,

00:00:16.980 --> 00:00:18.680
digital anthropology.

00:00:18.710 --> 00:00:20.460
I'm going to tell you a story.

00:00:20.470 --> 00:00:24.120
I had fun writing last night.

00:00:24.130 --> 00:00:26.980
OK, my name is Francisco.

00:00:26.990 --> 00:00:31.660
I have some background in AI safety and tools for thought.

00:00:31.670 --> 00:00:33.740
I've worked at Meter and the U Commission.

00:00:33.750 --> 00:00:37.440
And I run my own small R&D org called Ep

00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:38.140
istemic Garden.

00:00:38.150 --> 00:00:40.390
And we build AI tools for community flourishing.

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:45.520
Epistemic Garden.

00:00:45.530 --> 00:00:49.390
OK, so I spend a lot of time on Twitter.

00:00:49.410 --> 00:00:52.340
There's this part of Twitter that I love.

00:00:52.350 --> 00:00:56.280
And you could describe them as intellectual hippies.

00:00:56.290 --> 00:00:58.860
I think of them as pre-paradigmatic research

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:01.700
scene online.

00:01:01.710 --> 00:01:05.940
And these are people with varied interests, all of mine.

00:01:05.980 --> 00:01:12.240
There have been potentially many waves.

00:01:12.250 --> 00:01:15.260
This is how you can think of them.

00:01:15.310 --> 00:01:21.280
But the anthropology has always been done manually in pictures like this

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:21.680
one.

00:01:21.730 --> 00:01:30.240
I want to make the argument that it

00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:34.720
's a generative scene that ends up being very influential.

00:01:34.730 --> 00:01:36.300
You know the motto of the conference?

00:01:36.310 --> 00:01:39.840
I'm pretty-- I'm relatively confident that my friends came

00:01:39.840 --> 00:01:41.100
up with it way back when.

00:01:41.150 --> 00:01:45.730
The Department of War-- I know it's not a great

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:46.380
slide.

00:01:46.390 --> 00:01:50.160
But again, I'm making the argument that, mimetically

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:52.500
, this group of people is kind of upstream of a lot

00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:53.140
of stuff.

00:01:53.150 --> 00:01:58.600
OK, so I love these people.

00:01:58.610 --> 00:01:59.800
I love this space online.

00:01:59.810 --> 00:02:02.180
And I wanted to understand what makes it tick, what makes

00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:03.520
it work.

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:07.570
And I wanted to make it go even faster.

00:02:07.590 --> 00:02:08.780
But Twitter is closed.

00:02:08.790 --> 00:02:10.650
Oh, no.

00:02:10.670 --> 00:02:13.650
So I started something called the Community Archive.

00:02:13.670 --> 00:02:15.740
Because if I moved to Blue Sky-- I love Blue Sky

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:15.900
.

00:02:15.910 --> 00:02:17.840
But if I moved to Blue Sky, my people wouldn't

00:02:17.860 --> 00:02:18.520
be there.

00:02:18.530 --> 00:02:21.680
So I started this thing, and I got a few hundred

00:02:21.680 --> 00:02:23.680
people to upload their archives.

00:02:23.690 --> 00:02:25.540
You need to download them from Twitter.

00:02:25.550 --> 00:02:28.160
And it's a whole laborious process.

00:02:28.170 --> 00:02:31.180
But ultimately, we end up with a really nice data set

00:02:31.250 --> 00:02:33.900
to run experiments and build prototypes.

00:02:33.910 --> 00:02:36.700
You have a few influential people.

00:02:36.710 --> 00:02:38.080
In the top follows.

00:02:38.090 --> 00:02:40.000
Patio is like an ex-stripe person who

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:41.720
's a famous blogger.

00:02:41.730 --> 00:02:43.790
Emmett Scheer was CEO of OpenAI for like a

00:02:43.790 --> 00:02:44.420
second.

00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:51.680
And people did build all sorts of tools and prototypes.

00:02:51.690 --> 00:02:53.480
These are a few that I gathered.

00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:55.690
But you have like a Google Trends type thing.

00:02:55.740 --> 00:03:02.790
Someone did like an idea, like viral spread of ideas thing

00:03:02.790 --> 00:03:02.910
.

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:04.660
I have a banger bot over there.

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:08.650
Someone did people search on the archive.

00:03:08.780 --> 00:03:14.100
Many tools.

00:03:14.110 --> 00:03:17.020
But the tools don't answer my questions.

00:03:17.030 --> 00:03:21.470
I wanted to understand the stories and the flow of ideas in

00:03:21.550 --> 00:03:23.020
this community.

00:03:23.030 --> 00:03:26.550
So I tried semantic clustering first.

00:03:26.570 --> 00:03:28.430
You embed all the tweets.

00:03:28.450 --> 00:03:30.160
You try to cluster them.

00:03:30.170 --> 00:03:34.620
And you get groups of tweets that are a little bit too

00:03:34.620 --> 00:03:35.680
broad.

00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:41.040
So an example is you might end up with a cluster of

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:44.320
just broadly meditation-y themed things.

00:03:44.330 --> 00:03:45.210
But I want stories.

00:03:45.230 --> 00:03:50.090
I want threads of narrative that are much more specific than that

00:03:50.450 --> 00:03:50.620
.

00:03:50.630 --> 00:03:54.880
And I examined the meditation cluster.

00:03:54.890 --> 00:03:58.600
And found one really cool story.

00:03:58.610 --> 00:04:06.640
I think some Vietnamese Dharma person has the saying

00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:08.340
, like, the next Buddha is a Sangha.

00:04:08.350 --> 00:04:13.050
And over time, people kind of remixed this and all

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:19.170
the Dharma-oriented people made them, yeah, you know

00:04:19.220 --> 00:04:20.520
, like, the next Buddha is an internet community.

00:04:20.530 --> 00:04:25.950
And that's a story that you can tell, that I

00:04:25.950 --> 00:04:28.280
found in the data.

00:04:28.290 --> 00:04:30.900
But semantic clustering didn't work that well to do it

00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:32.780
in an automated, exhaustive way, right?

00:04:32.790 --> 00:04:36.540
So I tried to find strands, which worked better.

00:04:36.550 --> 00:04:38.350
So I'm going to tell you a little bit about strands

00:04:38.350 --> 00:04:38.540
.

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:41.510
They worked better.

00:04:41.550 --> 00:04:48.540
We took this tweet about community building, the original one,

00:04:48.550 --> 00:04:54.190
and we found tweets causally downstream of it and tweets top

00:04:54.220 --> 00:04:54.540
ically upstream of it.

00:04:54.550 --> 00:04:59.340
Like I was saying, strands are centered on one tweet,

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:05.780
like causal light cones, downstream, upstream, backwards and forwards

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:06.540
in time.

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:12.550
This is my working diagram, but it's what it says

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:14.300
on the tin.

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:17.290
And, oh yeah, I guess I could explain.

00:05:17.310 --> 00:05:19.400
It's like, you have a tweet, it gets quoted

00:05:19.400 --> 00:05:21.820
a bunch of times in the future, or it gets replied

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:25.220
to, and all of those are kind of causally upstream

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:26.070
, right?

00:05:26.090 --> 00:05:28.720
And you could implement the causally upstream in many ways.

00:05:28.730 --> 00:05:31.980
In my case, I just did semantic similarity, and it

00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:32.630
's close enough.

00:05:32.650 --> 00:05:34.980
We still get pretty cool results.

00:05:34.990 --> 00:05:38.680
Oh yeah, I forgot I had slides explaining exactly this.

00:05:38.690 --> 00:05:41.020
Quotes enriching with semantic search.

00:05:41.030 --> 00:05:44.760
And then you get all the threads from the quotes and the

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:46.060
replies and so on.

00:05:46.070 --> 00:05:48.620
And you end up with something that's kind of shaped like

00:05:48.630 --> 00:05:49.070
this.

00:05:49.090 --> 00:05:53.900
I analyzed a bunch of them manually just to make sure that

00:05:53.910 --> 00:05:55.430
the quality was right.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:06:01.920
Then I kind of automated them and got 250 of them.

00:06:01.930 --> 00:06:05.100
But what tweets do we base the strands on?

00:06:05.140 --> 00:06:08.840
Well, bangers, of course.

00:06:08.850 --> 00:06:12.770
Bangers are tweets with lots of quote tweets over time from

00:06:12.770 --> 00:06:14.850
the same community.

00:06:14.950 --> 00:06:18.540
That kind of implies that they're good enough to cite over

00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:22.330
and over and use as building blocks in the future when making

00:06:22.350 --> 00:06:23.140
arguments.

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:25.540
Works pretty well.

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:29.120
These are some of the bangers.

00:06:29.130 --> 00:06:32.700
If you're familiar with the community, you'll recognize these

00:06:32.710 --> 00:06:36.940
as pretty canonical tweets that end up being referenced over and over

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:37.200
.

00:06:37.210 --> 00:06:40.220
We found 250 of them.

00:06:40.250 --> 00:06:45.760
This is kind of a little semantic atlas of the strands

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:47.840
that we found.

00:06:47.850 --> 00:06:52.880
And you can ask, can you braid the strands together?

00:06:52.890 --> 00:06:53.920
Can we make a full picture?

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:57.920
Can we make a fuller map?

00:06:57.930 --> 00:07:01.020
I tried getting plot code to make sense of them because there

00:07:01.020 --> 00:07:04.230
's 250 of those.

00:07:04.330 --> 00:07:06.680
As visual support, this is the chaos of the data set

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:10.000
and these are the individual strands and this is what I'm

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:11.160
hoping for.

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:13.030
It's not perfect, but it's a start.

00:07:13.050 --> 00:07:15.680
It works fine.

00:07:15.690 --> 00:07:17.290
It still requires a lot of human care.

00:07:17.310 --> 00:07:19.660
I wouldn't trust it.

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:22.480
I wouldn't present the results without having already a tacit

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:25.860
knowledge of having been on Twitter for this long.

00:07:25.870 --> 00:07:29.320
But I think we can get there.

00:07:29.330 --> 00:07:32.140
So what can we say about the big history of the scene

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:32.450
?

00:07:32.470 --> 00:07:34.910
Well, these are walls of text, so I won't

00:07:34.910 --> 00:07:35.640
bore you.

00:07:35.650 --> 00:07:38.360
But the TLDR is there's this guy, Visa,

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:43.530
who figures out a bunch of really good posting norms that people

00:07:43.530 --> 00:07:47.200
end up adopting over time.

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:50.610
During COVID, lots of kind of rationalist-y,

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:53.820
dharma-y flavored people join Twitter.

00:07:53.830 --> 00:07:58.000
They find Visa's posting norms and it creates this kind of

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:03.700
really generative intellectual scene where people who are previously pretty rational

00:08:03.700 --> 00:08:07.580
ist-minded, pretty left brain, end up discovering all

00:08:07.590 --> 00:08:14.960
of these spiritual traditions and therapy modalities and embodied practices.

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:18.840
And that was kind of the golden age, but things keep

00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:19.600
going.

00:08:19.610 --> 00:08:23.280
This is just like the kind of the implications of that big

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:25.910
left brain, right brain merge.

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:28.050
And kind of the era that we've been in for the

00:08:28.050 --> 00:08:32.670
past couple of years, I guess, is characterized by community

00:08:32.820 --> 00:08:40.260
building in real life and data infrastructure, like the Community Arch

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:42.470
ive.

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:45.240
So we just found a bunch of stories.

00:08:45.250 --> 00:08:48.980
We have cloth code stitched them together.

00:08:48.990 --> 00:08:53.030
I have a personal theory of the scene.

00:08:53.050 --> 00:08:56.130
I don't think we're going to go through it very

00:08:56.130 --> 00:08:58.620
, very, very in depth.

00:08:58.630 --> 00:09:01.370
I will just say that I think the core loop of what

00:09:01.370 --> 00:09:06.500
's happening here is people who are high in epistemic

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:09.950
rigor, you know, like have the tools of rationality

00:09:09.960 --> 00:09:12.890
, like Bayesian thinking and so on and systems thinking,

00:09:12.890 --> 00:09:17.540
look at these old traditions and kind of try them out and

00:09:17.540 --> 00:09:21.340
explain them in rationalist terms, and that makes them more

00:09:21.380 --> 00:09:27.190
accessible to new people who are kind of like more left brain

00:09:27.190 --> 00:09:29.110
emphasis.

00:09:29.130 --> 00:09:32.350
Having access to these practices, they end up, you know

00:09:32.350 --> 00:09:35.800
, having more nervous system capacity and executive function, which lets

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:40.170
them relate to people that are doing, do more projects that

00:09:40.170 --> 00:09:45.690
has an outgrowth of community and friendship and flourishing and

00:09:45.690 --> 00:09:49.670
is all supported by, by, by technical infrastructure like Twitter

00:09:49.670 --> 00:09:53.540
, Blue Sky and tools that people may build on top.

00:09:53.550 --> 00:09:58.710
This is with overwhelming icons added I don't think it's

00:09:58.770 --> 00:10:00.680
worth looking at.

00:10:00.740 --> 00:10:04.040
There's still work to do.

00:10:04.050 --> 00:10:06.810
There are a few key events that I pre-register

00:10:06.810 --> 00:10:09.460
ed that I thought I would be able to find in the

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:11.920
data that I was not.

00:10:11.960 --> 00:10:14.660
And that's fine.

00:10:14.670 --> 00:10:16.660
For example, the first time the community met in person,

00:10:16.660 --> 00:10:18.660
there was this thing called VibeCamp.

00:10:18.670 --> 00:10:20.460
But Brook, the founder, isn't in the community archive

00:10:20.460 --> 00:10:20.660
.

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:23.880
So we couldn't really, like, find the strand exactly

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:24.650
for that.

00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:27.260
In the same way, jhanas, which are kind

00:10:27.260 --> 00:10:30.660
of meditation practice that became really big recently.

00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:31.640
But the main people aren't there.

00:10:31.670 --> 00:10:34.380
So it was hard to find, like, the strands that

00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:35.650
did exactly that.

00:10:35.670 --> 00:10:38.360
And then FractalNYC is an in-person

00:10:38.360 --> 00:10:42.860
community where the people are, in fact, present, but

00:10:42.860 --> 00:10:45.710
we still, you know, for one reason or another,

00:10:45.800 --> 00:10:47.660
didn't find a great strand.

00:10:47.670 --> 00:10:50.630
So, bless you.

00:10:50.670 --> 00:10:52.660
If the data-- yeah, OK.

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:55.830
Obviously, if we have complete data, this wouldn't be

00:10:55.830 --> 00:10:56.650
a problem.

00:10:56.670 --> 00:10:59.420
But the people I care about are still on Twitter, right

00:10:59.420 --> 00:10:59.650
?

00:10:59.670 --> 00:11:02.650
And we were talking about this on the panel just earlier.

00:11:02.670 --> 00:11:03.640
It's kind of a socio-technical problem.

00:11:03.670 --> 00:11:07.440
Maybe we need to throw a better party, even though the

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:08.650
house is really nice.

00:11:08.720 --> 00:11:09.620
Exactly.

00:11:09.720 --> 00:11:14.650
Yeah, so what's next for me?

00:11:14.670 --> 00:11:18.710
I'm building tools for community flourishing to, you know

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:22.290
, get 100x more serendipity if we can

00:11:22.370 --> 00:11:22.660
.

00:11:22.670 --> 00:11:25.540
Right now, like, the next thing I'm doing is

00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:29.490
kind of like a P2P network of permission data between

00:11:29.670 --> 00:11:33.460
people and to get-- to find opportunities between us, right

00:11:33.610 --> 00:11:33.660
?

00:11:33.670 --> 00:11:36.650
Like, Ronan's agent talks to my agent.

00:11:36.670 --> 00:11:38.660
Maybe I know someone who wants to fund Ronan.

00:11:38.670 --> 00:11:41.380
Maybe I'm trying to get rid of a couch and Ron

00:11:41.380 --> 00:11:42.650
an needs a couch.

00:11:42.670 --> 00:11:45.780
And the goal is to have this, you know, big

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:49.470
ecosystem of AI fairies conspiring in your favor.

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:53.650
This is where the fairies live.

00:11:53.670 --> 00:11:56.650
Yeah, this is Epistemic Garden.

00:11:56.670 --> 00:11:57.620
I'm Francisco.

00:11:57.670 --> 00:11:58.640
You can find me on Substack.

00:11:58.670 --> 00:12:02.650
I publish lab notes fairly regularly with my work.

00:12:02.670 --> 00:12:03.620
And thank you.

00:12:03.670 --> 00:12:05.660
Thank you, guys, for paying attention.

00:12:05.670 --> 00:12:06.640
Thanks, Francisco.

00:12:06.670 --> 00:12:07.620
You're welcome.

00:12:07.670 --> 00:12:08.620
Any questions?

00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:09.640
That's a lot of information.

00:12:09.660 --> 00:12:09.660
This was really fun.

00:12:09.670 --> 00:12:13.380
What do you-- you talked a little bit about limitations,

00:12:13.380 --> 00:12:14.660
but like, yeah, what do you wish you could build

00:12:14.660 --> 00:12:14.660
that you feel like you can't build?

00:12:14.670 --> 00:12:15.640
Or where are you limited?

00:12:15.670 --> 00:12:18.500
Like, you were saying there were some, like, events

00:12:18.500 --> 00:12:21.270
you were expecting to see that you didn't see, but

00:12:21.270 --> 00:12:24.400
are there, like, bigger things you're like, I

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:27.070
wish I could have this, but I don't have it

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:27.660
yet.

00:12:27.670 --> 00:12:30.540
I think definitely just the amount of data is one, right

00:12:30.560 --> 00:12:40.440
, just being comprehensive across all the people that might

00:12:41.210 --> 00:12:44.660
matter.

00:12:44.720 --> 00:12:51.790
Another is permission data, where, for the opportunity mining that

00:12:51.790 --> 00:12:56.110
I was talking about, you know, I don't want

00:12:56.220 --> 00:13:00.660
to be public about everything, but for people I meet once

00:13:00.660 --> 00:13:03.180
or twice at a conference or friends of friends, I wouldn

00:13:03.190 --> 00:13:03.660
't mind.

00:13:03.670 --> 00:13:07.490
There's a lot of information that would make it easy to

00:13:07.490 --> 00:13:11.750
coordinate with other people that I wouldn't be able to post

00:13:11.780 --> 00:13:12.570
onto it.

00:13:12.670 --> 00:13:14.760
I just got to say, I feel like the whole day

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:17.180
if I had to summarize it in, like, one sentence

00:13:17.180 --> 00:13:19.480
that I learned is that blue sky is a nice house,

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:21.580
but it needs to throw a better party.

00:13:21.670 --> 00:13:23.550
And I think, yeah, you can teach us how to

00:13:23.550 --> 00:13:24.650
throw good parties.

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:25.640
Like, this is cool stuff.

00:13:25.720 --> 00:13:26.620
Thanks.

00:13:26.670 --> 00:13:28.660
Yeah, so we should jam on it.

00:13:28.670 --> 00:13:29.640
Any other questions?

00:13:33.670 --> 00:13:42.150
You talked sort of briefly about, like, assembling threads from

00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:44.660
, like, posts.

00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:46.680
I was wondering if you could, like, elaborate a bit

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:47.650
more on that process.

00:13:47.670 --> 00:13:49.860
I felt like it was kind of unclear to me how you

00:13:49.920 --> 00:13:52.370
take one post and turn it into this whole, you know

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:55.510
, how do you find, like, posts that form some

00:13:55.510 --> 00:13:56.580
sort of story?

00:13:56.670 --> 00:13:57.640
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:13:57.670 --> 00:14:03.100
So I think the core insight-- I think the core insight

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:07.880
is that, first, we pick the central posts well,

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:11.660
because they're posts that are very likely to have mattered.

00:14:11.670 --> 00:14:15.650
And they have lots of quote tweets.

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:17.660
They're cited lots of times, right?

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:25.420
And then the actual way we build the strands is-- so

00:14:25.480 --> 00:14:27.660
you get the post.

00:14:27.670 --> 00:14:31.130
Then you take all the times it was quoted, all the

00:14:31.170 --> 00:14:33.660
posts that quote the original one.

00:14:33.700 --> 00:14:34.620
Right?

00:14:34.700 --> 00:14:37.650
Then we take all of those.

00:14:37.670 --> 00:14:40.650
We do semantic search on them and find, you know,

00:14:40.660 --> 00:14:43.280
the 50, if you want, you know, most sem

00:14:43.290 --> 00:14:47.600
antically similar posts, so that we have some chance of getting

00:14:47.600 --> 00:14:48.660
past posts, posts from the past.

00:14:48.670 --> 00:14:51.650
Because otherwise, it would be all in the future.

00:14:51.670 --> 00:14:55.650
Then for each of those, we get all their threads,

00:14:55.650 --> 00:14:55.660
right?

00:14:55.670 --> 00:14:57.660
Like, all the reply trees.

00:14:57.670 --> 00:15:01.650
And that gives us something that looks kind of like this.

